Rift Valley fever - Tanzania 980226204610
Date: Sun, 8 Mar 1998 18:33:17 -0600
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>
RIFT VALLEY FEVER IN TANZANIA

Text of a fax received on 3 March 1998 from Dr J.N. Melewas, Director of
Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, Dar es Salaam:
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: February 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: February 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
several villages in Arusha and
Kilimanjaro regions (northern Tanzania) 15

Description of affected population: traditional (agro-pastoral) livestock
sector of northern Tanzania - the Masai ecosystem. Three human cases were
reported in two villages.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species ovine 30 cases
caprine 29 cases
camel 34 cases
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Institute for Virology
(South Africa).
B. Diagnostic tests used: haemagglutination inhibition and
ELISA(enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: carrier state in natural hosts and
vectors.
B. Mode of spread: vector (mosquito) transmission and direct contact in
humans.
C. Other epidemiological details: effect of unusually heavy rains (El Nino)
causing massive build up of insect vectors.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine and movement control
inside the country; testing; control of arthropods.
